{"title_page": "Oliver Wyman", "text_new": "{{About|the company|the voice actor|Oliver Wyman (actor)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Oliver Wyman\n| logo                = Oliver-wyman-logo-2019.jpg\n| former_name         = Oliver, Wyman & Company; Mercer Oliver Wyman\n| type                = [[Subsidiary]] of [[Marsh & McLennan]]\n| num_locations       = 60+ offices\n| key_people          = [[Scott McDonald (CEO)]]\n| industry            = [[Management consulting]]\n| revenue             = {{Unbulleted list|{{Increase}} US $2.1&nbsp;billion (2019)}}\n| num_employees       = 5,000+ employees\n| homepage            = {{URL|http://www.oliverwyman.com}}\n| foundation          = {{start date and age|1984}}\n| parent              = [[Marsh & McLennan Companies]]\n| location            = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| hq_location_country = United States\n}}\n\n'''Oliver Wyman''' is an American global [[management consulting]] firm. Founded in [[New York City]] in 1984, the firm currently has more than 60 offices in [[Europe]], [[North America]], the [[Middle East]], and [[Asia-Pacific]], employing over 5,000 professionals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmc.com/content/mmc-web/global/en/about-us/overview/about-oliver-wyman.html|title=About Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=|website=Marsh & McLennan Companies|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It ranks among the best strategy consulting firms in the world in terms of prestige, growth, and employee satisfaction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://igotanoffer.com/blogs/mckinsey-case-interview-blog/top-consulting-firms|title=The 9 most prestigious consulting firms in the world|last=|first=|date=2018-02-26|website=IGotAnOffer|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consulting.com/top-consulting-firms|title=The Top 50 Consulting Firms In 2019 By Revenue, Prestige, Growth & Employee Satisfaction|last=|first=|date=|website=Consulting.com|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902194211/https://www.consulting.com/top-consulting-firms|archive-date=September 2, 2019|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe firm is part of the Oliver Wyman Group, a business unit of [[Marsh & McLennan]].\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1984, six consultants left [[Booz Allen Hamilton]] to start their own consulting firm. Alexander Oliver and William (Bill) Wyman, both partners at Booz, wanted to create a company that would specialize and excel at consulting a certain industry at a time when most other firms were trying to become generalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1983/1010/136.html#2d26b9997dfb|title=Are All These Consultants Really Necessary?|last=|first=|date=1983-10-10|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver, Wyman & Company decided to focus on work with large financial institutions.<ref>Ucok, Evren (1 Oct 1998). Re: [https://www.math.upenn.edu/~ted/Majors/Wyman.html \"Oliver, Wyman & Company\"] Message to Ted Chinburg. ''University of Pennsylvania, Department of Mathematics.''</ref>\n\nBill Wyman left the firm in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/27096/000112528205002712/b406885_ex99-1.txt|title=William W. Wyman Joins Datascope's Board of Directors|last=|first=|date=2005-05-19|website=United States Securities & Exchange Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He felt that the human side of consulting was taking a backseat to the analytical work which clients increasingly demanded.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Thompson|first=Roger|url=https://www.alumni.hbs.edu/stories/Pages/story-bulletin.aspx?num=974|title=NEW PROGRAM HELPS RESTLESS ALUMS ANSWER THE QUESTION, 'WHAT'S NEXT?'|date=2011-06-01|work=Harvard Business School Alumni Stories|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112041207/https://www.alumni.hbs.edu/stories/Pages/story-bulletin.aspx?num=974|archive-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n== Growth ==\nOliver Wyman is notable for a complex history of mergers & acquisitions. ''Management Consulted'' magazine wrote that \"[t]he history entails so many reorganizations and changing of org charts that the archives would confuse even the most intelligent consultants themselves.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://managementconsulted.com/consulting-interviews/oliver-wyman-interview/|title=Oliver Wyman Profile and Interview Preparation: The Inside Story|last=|first=|date=2013-08-01|website=Management Consulted|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2008, [[Harvard Business School]] published a case documenting how the acquisitions were restructured and rebranded to create a preeminent firm based on specialization and industry expertise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hbsp.harvard.edu/product/409055-PDF-ENG?it=|title=Rebranding at Oliver Wyman Group|last=Eccles|first=Robert|last2=Simpson|first2=Kaitlyn|date=|website=Harvard Business School Publishing|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the oldest organization now incorporated into the company can be traced back to 1969,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://virtualglobetrotting.com/map/james-r-barkers-house/|title=James R. Barker's House in Darien, CT|last=|first=|date=2019-01-22|website=Virtual Globetrotting|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> the modern firm was created in 2003 through a merger of Oliver, Wyman & Company with [[Mercer (consulting firm)|Mercer]]'s financial services strategy & risk units.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipe.com/mercer-confirms-oliver-wyman-buy/6674.article|title=Mercer confirms Oliver Wyman buy|last=Avery|first=Helen|date=2003-02-25|website=International Publishers Limited|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The acquisition came towards the end of a wave of purchases by Mercer in the United States, including consultancies Temple, Barker & Sloane bought in 1987,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Deutsch|first=Claudia H.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/10/business/what-s-new-in-management-consulting-the-corporate-clamor-for-help-gets-louder.html|title=WHAT'S NEW IN MANAGEMENT CONSULTING; The Corporate Clamor for Help Gets Louder|date=1988-07-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Strategic Planning Associates in 1989,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/business/1990/06/18/mr-consultant/3492fb02-44a2-44f4-bbe6-3d4b24747b7c/|title=Mr. Consultant|last=Potts|first=Mark|date=1990-06-18|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and [[David A. Nadler|David Nadler]]'s Delta Consulting Group which became \"Mercer Delta\" in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrhub.com/doc/mercer-consulting-group-plans-acquisition-of-0001|title=Mercer Consulting Group Plans Acquisition of Delta Consulting|last=|first=|date=2000-03-24|editor-last=Woolsey|editor-first=Christine|website=HR Hub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20040726005683/en/David-Nadler-Named-Top-25-Consultants-Chairman|title=David Nadler Named One of Top 25 Consultants; Chairman and CEO of Mercer Delta Makes Consulting Magazine's 2004 List|last=Murphy|first=Emma|date=2004-07-26|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In Europe, they acquired the Swiss-German firm Unternehmensberatung Munchen in 1993,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/62709/0000912057-95-001755.txt|title=ANNUAL REPORT PURSUANT TO SECTION 13 OR 15(D) OF THE SECURITIES EXCHANGE ACT OF 1934|last=|first=|date=1995-03-28|website=United States Securities & Exchange Commission Archives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> French firm Marketing Innovation Design pour l'industrie in 1995<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lesechos.fr/1996/07/rachats-et-redeploiements-dans-le-conseil-en-1995-838814|title=Rachats et red\u00e9ploiements dans le conseil en 1995|last=|first=|date=1996-07-25|website=Les Echos|language=fr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and Corporate Decisions, Inc., a firm founded by ex-[[Bain & Company]] partners that operated in the US, UK, and France in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://freakonomics.com/2012/11/26/i-consult-therefore-i-am-full-transcript/|title=I Consult, Therefore I Am (Ep. 102): Full Transcript|last=Freakonomics|date=2012-11-26|website=Freakonomics|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Mercer (consulting firm)|Mercer]] became the world's largest benefit consultant with one billion dollars in 1997 revenue, and much of their growth was attributed to these acquisitions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsurance.com/article/19980830/STORY/10005392/DEAL-WILL-PUT-MERCER-FAR-AHEAD-OF-RIVALS|title=DEAL WILL PUT MERCER FAR AHEAD OF RIVALS|last=Geisel|first=Jerry|date=1998-08-30|website=Business Insurance|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1997-03-13-1997072016-story.html|title=$1.8&nbsp;billion deal creates world's largest broker Marsh & McLennan buys Johnson & Higgins amid shrinking industry profits|last=|first=|date=1997-03-13|website=The Baltimore Sun|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThis pattern of growth by acquisition has continued to the present day, with Oliver Wyman or its predecessors acquiring more than 20 firms in the 21st century.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=2NIaAQAAMAAJ&dq=Dr.+Seebauer+|title=Mercer Management Consulting|publisher=WetFeet|year=2000|isbn=978-1-58207-035-3|location=|pages=9|language=en}}</ref> Although the acquisitions have been economically beneficial, they have hurt the firm's brand recognition as acquired companies are retitled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caseinterview.com/top-consulting-firms|title=Top Consulting Firms|last=Cheng|first=Victor|date=2020-01-09|website=CaseInterview.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Former [[Mercer (consulting firm)|Mercer]] CEO Peter Coster heard the corporate units being referred to as \"Mercer & What's Its Face\" due to confusion after a series of rapid name changes.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Cuff|first=Daniel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/18/business/business-people-a-briton-is-to-head-william-m-mercer.html|title=BUSINESS PEOPLE; A Briton Is to Head William M. Mercer|date=1987-06-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Pollack|first2=Andrew|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n=== Temple, Barker & Sloane ===\n[[File:Temple-barker-sloane.png|thumb|360x360px|James Barker, Carl Sloane, and Herbert \"Peter\" Temple III|alt=|left]]Founded in Lexington, Massachusetts in 1969, Temple, Barker & Sloane found quick success in the management consulting industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dignitymemorial.com/obituaries/salem-ma/carl-sloane-6533995|title=Carl Sloane Obituary - Salem, MA|last=|first=|date=2015-07-28|website=Dignity Memorial|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In a candid interview with ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'', Carl Sloane said \"In the 1960s, if you had a Harvard MBA, a blue serge suit, and an air travel card, you were a consultant.\" But as the recession of the 1980s began, he noted that \"Now the clients have their own bright MBAs, and you have to offer a range of specialized services.<nowiki>''</nowiki><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bradley|first=Barbara|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1983/0104/010439.html|title=Recession changes focus of management consulting|date=1983-01-04|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=|url-status=live|issn=0882-7729}}</ref>\n\nTemple, Barker & Sloane found themselves specializing in [[supply chain management]], [[transport]]ation, and [[financial services]]. They conducted studies for the [[United States Coast Guard]] to determine if the nation should sign onto international oil protocols in the 70s;<ref>Goldberg, Victor P. \u201cRecovery for Economic Loss Following the Exxon \u2018Valdez\u2019 Oil Spill.\u201d ''The Journal of Legal Studies'', vol. 23, no. 1, 1994, pp. 1. ''JSTOR'', [https://www.jstor.org/stable/724301 www.jstor.org/stable/724301].</ref> restructured [[APL (shipping company)|American Presidential Lines]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1983/1010/136.html|title=Are All These Consultants Really Necessary?|last=|first=|date=1983-10-09|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which became the largest American shipping company in the Pacific in the 80s;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf4j49n761/admin/#bioghist-1.7.3|title=Guide to the American President Lines Records, 1871-1995|last=|first=|date=|website=Online Archive of California|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and found alternate uses for state-owned railcars when freight trains declined in popularity in the 90s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/CZIC-tf320-a48-1986/html/CZIC-tf320-a48-1986.htm|title=Alternative uses of the railcar ferry S.S. Chief Wawatam State of Michigan Dept. of Transportation, State of Michigan Dept. of Natural Resources|last=1986-04|date=|website=U.S. Government Printing Office|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm also employed Burunda Prince, who would go on to become the first female consultant of color at [[Bain & Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digsouthtechsummit.com/agenda/speakers/425260|title=Burunda Prince|last=|first=|date=|website=DIG South Tech Summit|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atlantatribune.com/2018/06/20/why-burunda-prince-jones-came-home-to-the-farm/|title=Why Burunda Prince-Jones Came Home to The Farm|last=|first=|date=2018-06-20|website=Atlanta Tribune|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, the chairman of the firm's board gave an expert testimony analyzing the impacts of the [[Energy Policy and Conservation Act]] based on Temple, Barker & Sloane's experience in the marine transportation industry. U.S. Congressman [[Edward Garmatz]] proclaimed it the best presentation he had \"ever seen or heard in [his] many years here in the Congress.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9k9V7WOnOjoC&pg=PA37&lpg=PA37&dq=temple+barker+#v=onepage|title=Cargo for American Ships: Hearings, Ninety-second Congress, First Session|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|year=1972|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of acquisition, the firm was worth an estimated $45&nbsp;million in 1987 US dollars, or over $100&nbsp;million today.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-11-25-fi-16363-story.html|title=Archive|last=|first=|date=1987-11-25|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.joc.com/insurance-briefs_19871124.html|title=INSURANCE BRIEFS|last=|first=|date=1984-11-24|website=JOC.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Mercer Management Consulting ===\nTemple, Barker & Sloane (TBS) was merged with Strategic Planning Associates (SPA) to form \"Mercer Management Consulting\" in 1990, a business unit specializing in risk and financial services.<ref>{{Cite book|last=United Nations Conference on Trade and Development. Programme on Transnational Corporations|title=Management Consulting: A Survey of the Industry and Its Largest Firms|publisher=United Nations|year=1993|isbn=9211044197|location=New York|pages=72\u201379}}</ref> The two firms had markedly different cultures, with TBS focusing on industry-specific expertise-based consulting,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=DeLong|first=Thomas J.|last2=Echenberg|first2=Michael|date=2002-07-25|title=Mercer Management Consulting (A)|url=https://www.hbs.edu/faculty/Pages/item.aspx?num=29192|journal=Harvard Business School Case Collection|language=en-us|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> while SPA applied value-based planning models to a broad range of industries.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woo|first=Carolyn|date=1984-09-01|title=An Empirical Test of Value-Based Planning Models and Implications|journal=Management Science|volume=30|issue=9|pages=1031\u20131050|doi=10.1287/mnsc.30.9.1031|jstor=2631722}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Horwitch|first=Mel|date=1978-06-01|title=The Emergence of Post-Modern Strategic Management|journal=Working Paper (Sloan School of Management)|volume=|pages=|hdl=1721.1/47781}}</ref> Their integration was slow and painful, and by 1992, Dean L. Wilde II and Dean R. Silverman were one of the fewer remaining senior members from Strategic Planning Associates still at the company. They had started their own consulting firm on the side known as \"Dean & Company Strategic Consulting\" and attempted to recruit other Mercer employees to join.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/920/219/1461548/|title=Mercer Management Consulting, Inc. v. Wilde, 920 F. Supp. 219 (D.D.C. 1996)|last=|first=|date=1996-03-29|website=Justia Law|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1996, Mercer successfully sued them for rendering competitive services and violating non-compete agreements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dc.findacase.com/research/wfrmDocViewer.aspx/xq/fac.19960329_0000082.DDC.htm/qx|title=MERCER MGMT. CONSULTING v. WILDE|last=|first=|date=1996-03-29|website=FindACase|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMercer Management Consulting continued to grow,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.hbr.org/product/mercer-management-consulting-s-grow-to-be-great-b-going-ahead-with-the-book/697087|title=Mercer Management Consulting's \"Grow to Be Great\" (B): Going Ahead with the Book|last=Knoop|first=Carin-Isabel|date=1997-04-04|website=Harvard Business Review Store|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> developing increasingly specialized industry knowledge and a global reach.<ref>Baptista, Jo\u00e3o & Morrison, David. (2002). [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/304752752_Mercer_Management_Consulting Mercer Management Consulting]. 10.1057/9781403907189_25.</ref> The firm took on projects for larger, international organizations such as the [[World Bank]],<ref>Institute of Medicine (US) Committee on Contraceptive Research and Development; Harrison PF, Rosenfield A, editors. Contraceptive Research and Development: Looking to the Future. Washington (DC): National Academies Press (US); 1996. 5, The Market for New Contraceptives: Translating Unmet Need into Market Demand. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK232764/</ref> [[IBM]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www-03.ibm.com/press/us/en/pressrelease/1792.wss|title=IBM and Mercer Management Consulting Form Strategic Alliance|last=|first=|date=2000-04-05|website=IBM|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and [[International Finance Corporation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.joc.com/maritime-news/privatization-black-sea-shipping-embroiled-political-imbroglio_19940213.html|title=PRIVATIZATION OF BLACK SEA SHIPPING EMBROILED IN POLITICAL IMBROGLIO|last=Tirschwell|first=Peter M.|date=1994-02-13|website=JOC.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/903191469672211019/pdf/164370REPLACEM0gebank0please0fix0it.pdf|title=Private Financing of Toll Roads|last=Fisher|first=Gregory|last2=Babber|first2=Suman|date=|website=World Bank Curated Documents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They increased their work with [[government]]s, restructuring [[Polish State Railways]] and helping privatize the [[Argentina|Argentinian]] commuter rail network.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Conference on Trade and Development Programme on Transnational Corporations|first=United Nations|url=https://books.google.com/?id=81C1AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&dq=Mercer+Management+Consulting#v=onepage|title=Management Consulting: A Survey of the Industry and Its Largest Firms|publisher=United Nations|year=1993|isbn=978-92-1-104419-5|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>[[File:Marsh & McLennan 9-11 Memorial.jpg|thumb|280x280px|A memorial to [[Marsh & McLennan Companies|Marsh & McLennan]] employees who died in the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 attacks]], reading \"Our lost colleagues are, above all, your adored children and parents, husbands and wives, sisters and brothers, your cherished relatives and friends.\"]]\nBut in 2001, the firm was severely affected by the [[September 11 attacks|9/11]] [[terrorist attacks]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.finextra.com/newsarticle/3138/marsh--mclennan-313-staff-missing-from-wtc1|title=Marsh & McLennan: 313 staff missing from WTC#1|last=|first=|date=2001-09-17|website=Finextra Research|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kellardmedia.com/tim-haviland-911-victim-absolutely-loved-new-york|title=Joseph Kellard's story on Tim Haviland, a 9/11 victim who moved to New York from Minnesota.|last=Kellard|first=Joseph|date=|website=KellardMedia|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Their [[parent company]], [[Marsh & McLennan Companies|Marsh & McLennan]], had nearly 2,000 employees working in both towers of the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] that day. The first plane crashed into the 93rd through 99th floors of Tower 1, which were owned by Marsh and occupied by 845 employees.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Greenberg|first=Jeffrey W.|url=https://hbr.org/2002/10/september-11-2001-a-ceos-story|title=September 11, 2001: A CEO's Story|date=2002-10-01|work=Harvard Business Review|access-date=|url-status=live|issue=October 2002|issn=0017-8012}}</ref> A total of 295 employees and 63 consultants died in the attack, including 1 who was aboard the hijacked aircraft.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-jersey/fortlee/911-stories-no-one-there-got-out-alive|title=9/11 Stories: No One There Got Out Alive|last=Piccirillo|first=Ann|date=2011-09-02|website=New Jersey Patch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Mercer Management Consulting was restructured in the aftermath of the incident, and their [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C]] and [[Geneva]] offices were shuttered.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glater|first=Jonathan D.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/06/business/company-news-mercer-consulting-is-closing-two-offices.html|title=Company News; Mercer Consulting Is Closing Two Offices|date=2001-11-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Glater|first=Jonathan D.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/04/business/dear-new-employee-welcome-and-goodbye.html|title=Dear New Employee: Welcome, and Goodbye|date=2001-05-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n=== Mercer Delta Consulting ===\nStarting with Delta Consulting Group in 2000, \"Mercer Delta Consulting\" grew through the acquisitions of Canadian Johnston Smith International, French Change Management Consultants, Spanish c.r.m. Concord, and American CDR International.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oliverwyman.com/our-culture/our-values/our-history.html|title=A HISTORY OF FORWARD THINKING|last=|first=|date=|website=Oliver Wyman|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The unit's speciality was in leadership and organizational change,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.plansponsor.com/storms-to-run-mercer-hr-consulting-in-mmc-reorg/|title=Storms to Run Mercer HR Consulting in MMC Reorg|last=Schneyer|first=Fred|date=2005-01-26|website=PLANSPONSOR|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20051101006025/en/Mercer-Delta-Consulting-Announces-Leadership-Transition-Mercer|title=Mercer Delta Consulting Announces Leadership Transition; Mercer Delta Veteran David R. Bliss Appointed CEO; Marking 25 Years as CEO, Founder David A. Nadler, Ph.D. Continues as Chairman|last=Parkel|first=Kerstein|date=2005-11-01|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and they routinely surveyed directors of the [[Fortune 1000]] to monitor developments in business governance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.usc.eduhttps//news.usc.edu/23451/Directors-Exert-More-Influence-in-Boardroom/|title=Directors Exert More Influence in Boardroom|last=|first=|date=2005-04-04|website=University of Southern California News|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn contrast to the traditional organizational structure, where business units within an organization are clearly defined, Mercer Delta Consulting was a proponent of strategically aligned business units that were \"linked\" to a larger organization with which they could share capabilities when needed, and operate separately from when they were not.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.economist.com/special-report/2006/01/21/partners-in-wealth|title=Partners in wealth|date=|work=The Economist|access-date=|url-status=live|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\n=== Mercer Oliver Wyman ===\nBy 2003, Mercer Management Consulting was ranked as the 6th best consulting firm while Oliver, Wyman & Company was the 9th, according to [[Vault.com|Vault]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20030902005713/en/New-Vault-Consulting-Guide-Released----McKinsey|title=New Vault Consulting Guide Released -- McKinsey, BCG, Bain Top Ranking|last=Boldeskou|first=Elena|date=2003-09-02|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Mercer's strengths at the time were in [[insurance]], [[asset management]], and retail [[broking]]; while Oliver, Wyman & Company's were in [[capital market]]s and [[investment banking]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fnlondon.com/articles/mercer-and-oliver-wyman-to-avoid-staff-cuts-in-merger-20030225|title=Mercer and Oliver Wyman to avoid staff cuts in merger|last=Adams|first=Jeremy|date=2003-02-25|website=Financial News|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The merger consolidated the two industry-leading firms into \"Mercer Oliver Wyman\" and was widely considered a success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20030224005417/en/Mercer-Oliver-Wyman-Company-Announce-Agreement|title=Mercer and Oliver, Wyman & Company Announce Agreement|last=|first=|date=2003-02-24|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In the years after, Mercer Oliver Wyman experienced rapid growth up to 25% annually, and was the fastest-growing consultancy in the top 10.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mahanta|first=Vinod|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/oliver-wyman-ceo-john-drzik-on-the-vagaries-of-global-financial-system/articleshow/19972062.cms|title=Oliver Wyman CEO John Drzik on the vagaries of global financial system|date=2013-05-10|work=The Economic Times|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Thakur|first2=Shirsha}}</ref>\n\n=== Oliver Wyman ===\n[[File:Oliver Wyman Milan Office.jpg|alt=An Oliver Wyman office lounge in Milan, Italy|thumb|272x272px|An Oliver Wyman office lounge in [[Milan]], [[Italy]]|left]]\nIn 2007, Mercer Management Consulting, Mercer Delta Organizational Consulting, and Mercer Oliver Wyman were consolidated into \"Oliver Wyman\" in an effort to address a broader range of client needs and streamline branding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20070509/FREE/70509006/marsh-mclennan-rebrands-consulting-units|title=Marsh & McLennan rebrands consulting units|last=Jones|first=David|date=2007-05-09|website=Crain's New York Business|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsurance.com/article/20070509/STORY/200010177/Mercer-units-combine-to-form-new-consultancy|title=Mercer units combine to form new consultancy|last=Hofmann|first=Mark A.|date=2007-05-09|website=Business Insurance|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The renamed firm was ranked 7th best until 2013, when it regained Mercer Management Consulting's previous ranking as 6th. In 2017, it climbed above [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]] to reach a new high as the 5th best consulting firm in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vault.com/best-companies-to-work-for/consulting/vault-consulting-rankings-top-50/year/2017|title=2017 Vault Consulting Rankings|last=|first=|date=|website=Vault|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n\"Oliver Wyman\" is also used as the namesake of a larger business unit within [[Marsh & McLennan Companies]], known as \"Oliver Wyman Group\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insurancejournal.com/news/national/2013/12/03/312809.htm|title=Marsh & McLennan Promotes McDonald to Lead Oliver Wyman Group|last=|first=|date=2013-12-03|website=Insurance Journal|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The group includes two other consulting firms which operate as sister companies: [[NERA Economic Consulting]] and [[Lippincott (brand consultancy)|Lippincott]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vault.com/company-profiles/management-strategy/oliver-wyman|title=Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=|website=Vault|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nFrom 2013 to 2019, Oliver Wyman Group grew at an average rate of 7% per year, outperforming the growth of the global management consulting market,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy.eu/news/3881/consulting-firm-oliver-wyman-books-6-growth-to-21-billion|title=Consulting firm Oliver Wyman books 6% growth to $2.1&nbsp;billion|last=|first=|date=2020-02-24|website=Consultancy Europe|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> despite experiencing a drop in revenue in 2016 after [[Brexit]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/3307ccef-454d-3db5-8255-3e2f7c85ab21|title=Oliver Wyman takes hit from Brexit uncertainty|last=Gray|first=Alistar|date=2016-10-25|website=The Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Services ==\nAs a global [[management consulting]] firm, Oliver Wyman provides advice and analysis on how companies can improve their performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themuse.com/advice/good-to-know-why-companies-really-hire-consultants|title=Good to Know: Why Companies Really Hire Consultants|last=Nuth|first=Alexandra|date=|website=The Muse|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm undertakes a variety of notable projects in the [[Automotive industry|automotive]], [[Defense industry|defense]], [[education]], [[Energy industry|energy]], [[Healthcare industry|healthcare]], [[telecommunication]]s, [[transport]]ation, and [[Travel industry|travel]] industries, but is particularly distinguished in the [[financial services]] sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/best-management-consulting-firms/|title=America's Best Management Consulting Firms|last=|first=|date=2019-03-19|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Through its partners, the company regularly contributes to business publications such as the ''[[Harvard Business Review]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', and [[Financial Times|''The Financial Times'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myconsultingcoach.com/news/oliver-wyman|title=Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=2018-02-27|website=My Consulting Coach|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It generates over $500,000 in revenue per consultant,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.careers-in-business.com/consulting/consrank09.htm|title=Management Consulting Firm Rankings: 2009|last=|first=|date=|website=Careers In Business|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firmsconsulting.com/quarterly/part-twelve-oliver-wyman/|title=Application Process, Part Twelve: Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=|website=Firms Consulting|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a figure that is more than double the national average and comes in second only to [[McKinsey & Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/936909/management-consultancies-worldwide-revenue-per-consultant/|title=Management consultancies: revenue per consultant 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=Statista|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bdimuccio.wordpress.com/2009/02/03/benchmarking-revenue-per-headcount-does-size-matter/|title=Benchmarking Revenue per Consultant Headcount: Does Size Matter?|last=Di Muccio|first=Bob|date=2009-02-03|website=Dataviews|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 1983 USDA investigation ===\nIn 1983, the firm was commissioned by the [[United States Department of Agriculture|U.S. Department of Agriculture]] to investigate allegations of poor meat and poultry regulations by environmental activist [[Ralph Nader]]. When Nader discovered that the USDA's response had been contracted out, he called the project a \"deplorable waste of taxpayers' money.\" A spokesperson from the Agricultural Department confirmed that Temple, Barker & Sloane had a blanket contract for $100,000 and stated \"We did ask them to look into the Nader charges and some other miscellaneous assignments... It's not unusual to have an outside firm take a look at it when serious charges are made against the department.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/06/26/Consumer-activist-Ralph-Nader-Sunday-called-the-Agriculture-Departments/7522425448000/|title=Consumer activist Ralph Nader Sunday called the Agriculture Department|last=|first=|date=1983-06-26|website=United Press International|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> After reading the firm's report, U.S. Representative [[Tom Harkin]] decided not to conduct hearings into Nader's charges, declaring that he was \"satisfied the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]] is not imperiling the nation's meat and poultry inspection program\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/newspage/131727783/|title=The Des Moines Register from Des Moines, Iowa on March 8, 1983 \u00b7 Page 4|last=|first=|date=1983-03-08|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2006 Irish Bank endorsement ===\nIn 2007, Oliver Wyman proclaimed the [[Anglo Irish Bank|Anglo-Irish Bank]] (AIB) as the 'best bank in the world' at the [[World Economic Forum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/best-bank-in-the-world-soon-turned-into-a-black-hole-36988122.html|title='Best bank in the world' soon turned into a black hole|last=Gretchen|first=Friemann|date=2018-06-07|website=independent.ie|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A year later, on March 17, 2008, the Irish stock market plunged as investors globally dumped shares in fear of the United States [[subprime mortgage crisis]]. The property bubble in Ireland burst, and the AIB's investments were heavily exposed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/st-patricks-day-massacre-of-2008-disaster-hits-financial-markets-36709981.html|title=St Patrick's Day Massacre of 2008: Disaster hits financial markets|last=O'Donovan|first=Donal|date=2018-03-18|website=Irish Independent|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The price of their stock collapsed in what became known as the St. Patrick's Day Massacre,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-26068425|title=Bank collapse 'known as massacre'|date=2014-02-06|work=BBC News|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref> and the bank ultimately needed $30&nbsp;billion in government bailouts to be nationalised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centralbank.ie/news/article/lars-frisell-financial-safety-net-conference-in-stockholm|title=Resolution of the Irish banking crisis: Hard-earned lessons for Europe|last=|first=|date=2015-05-19|website=Central Bank of Ireland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman faced criticism for their earlier endorsement.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Waterfield|first=Bruno|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/financialcrisis/10333310/ECB-hires-controversial-Wyman-for-bank-stress-tests.html|title=ECB hires controversial Wyman for bank stress tests|date=2013-09-25|work=The Telegraph|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The firm responded by saying that the 2006 \u201cbest bank\u201d accolade was based solely on a backward-looking review of shareholder returns. In a statement to the ''[[Financial Times]]'', they said \u201cToday one sees that differently. It would not have been a good idea to invest in Anglo Irish... We also unfortunately did not forecast the financial crisis in 2006.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9639e43e-2530-11e3-b349-00144feab7de|title=Consultants who praised defunct bank to advise on ECB review|last=Steen|first=Michael|date=2013-09-24|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe event damaged Oliver Wyman's reputation in Ireland, with future assignments coming under heavy scrutiny. In 2012, the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' discovered that Oliver Wyman consultants were staying at the luxury [[Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts|Four Seasons hotel]] while working on a project for [[Permanent TSB]]. When asked about the cost, a spokesperson from Permanent TSB stated that \"we cannot comment on what arrangements individual consultants have in respect of accommodation... a number of different hotels in Dublin are being used by different individuals.\" The Wyman group checked out of the hotel on the next day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/controversial-finance-experts-called-in-to-help-permanent-tsb-26853502.html|title=Controversial finance experts called in to help Permanent TSB|last=Keenan|first=Mark|date=2012-05-12|website=Irish Independent|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nDespite this incident, the firm continues to be hired widely in Europe and has audited 130 of the largest banks in the eurozone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://euobserver.com/economic/121554|title=ECB hires controversial consultancy for bank audit|last=Pop|first=Valentina|date=2013-09-25|website=EU Observer|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman ran the tests that set the terms of the [[2008\u20132014 Spanish financial crisis|2012 Spanish bailout]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cei.org/blog/real-spanish-bank-bailout-cost-113-billion-euro|title=The Real Spanish Bank Bailout Cost: 113&nbsp;Billion Euro|last=Melchiorre|first=Matthew|date=2012-10-01|website=Competitive Enterprise Institute|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> prevented the privatization of [[Slovenia|Slovene]] banks in 2013,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/slovenia-banks-idUSL6N0GR2B220130828|title=Delay tests nerves as Slovenia's bad bank sits on its hands|date=2013-08-28|work=Reuters|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> and advised on the sale of rescued Italian banks in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy.uk/news/3251/oliver-wyman-to-advise-on-sale-of-rescued-italian-banks|title=Oliver Wyman to advise on sale of rescued Italian banks|last=|first=|date=2016-02-02|website=Consultancy.uk|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm is hired particularly often by the \"troika\" of international lenders: the [[European Central Bank]], the [[European Commission]], and the [[International Monetary Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://euobserver.com/investigations/122415|title=Troika consultancies: A multi-million euro business beyond scrutiny|last=Pop|first=Valentina|date=2013-12-16|website=EUobserver|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012 LIBOR decommission===\nHailed as the world's most important number, the London Inter-Bank Offered Rate, or [[Libor|LIBOR]], is an interest rate used as a benchmark for an estimated $340&nbsp;trillion financial contracts worldwide.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cruise|first=Sinead|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-libor-transition-analysis-idUSKBN1WN0H4|title=The end of Libor: the biggest banking challenge you've never heard of|date=2019-10-08|work=Reuters|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=White|first2=Lawrence|language=en}}</ref> In 2012, Oliver Wyman was hired by the [[British Bankers' Association]] to provide technical assistance in reviewing how the rate was set after a preliminary investigation uncovered significant fraud and collusion among banks.<ref name=\"rolling\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/everything-is-rigged-the-biggest-financial-scandal-yet-20130425|title=Everything Is Rigged: The Biggest Price-Fixing Scandal Ever|last=Taibbi|first=Mark|date=2013-04-25|website=Rolling Stone|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref> Although LIBOR had lost the confidence of market participants after the investigation, it was unclear whether there was a rate that could replace it. Oliver Wyman urged caution during the transition period, pointing out that \u201c[s]ince the proposed alternative rates are calculated differently, payments under contracts referencing the new rates will differ from those referencing LIBOR. The transition will change firms\u2019 market risk profiles, requiring changes to risk models, valuation tools, product design and hedging strategies.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gfmag.com/magazine/january-2019/fear-and-loathing-road-libors-demise|title=Global Finance Magazine - Fear And Loathing On The Road To Libor's Demise|last=Hawser|first=Anita|date=2019-01-01|website=Global Finance Magazine|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The report projected that banks would need to spend an astonishing $1.2&nbsp;billion to transition away from LIBOR.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/08/reuters-america-analysis-the-end-of-libor-the-biggest-banking-challenge-youve-never-heard-of.html|title=ANALYSIS-The end of Libor: the biggest banking challenge you've never heard of|last=Cruise|first=Sinead|last2=White|first2=Lawrence|date=2019-10-08|website=CNBC|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In accordance with these conclusions, the UK [[Financial Conduct Authority]] decided to decommission LIBOR gradually, with official discontinuation set for 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gfoa.org/news/31016|title=LIBOR to Be Discontinued, SOFR to Replace It|last=|first=|date=2018-09-19|website=Government Finance Officers Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Oliver Wyman was hired by the [[International Swaps and Derivatives Association]] to address a similar case of manipulation of the worldwide common [[reference rate|reference rate value]] for fixed [[interest rate swap]] rates, also known as [[ISDAfix|ISDAFIX]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.finregalert.com/isda-hires-consultant-oliver-wyman-to-advise-on-isdafix-prices/|title=ISDA Hires Consultant Oliver Wyman to Advise on ISDAfix Prices|last=Leising|first=Matthew|date=2013-04-13|website=TradeWeb|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm invented the current methodology to calculate the value based on regulated [[Electronic trading platform|electronic trading]] quotes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://primefinancedisputes.org/files/2017-02/handjinicolaou-george-ice-swap-rate-jan-22-2017.pdf|title=ISDAFix: An Example of seamless Benchmark transition|last=Handjinicolaou|first=George|date=2017-01-23|website=Panel of Recognized International Market Experts in Finance Annual Conference|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 Kuwaiti joint venture ===\nIn 2013, the [[Kuwait Investment Authority]] and [[Kuwait Fund for Arab Economic Development]] announced a joint venture with Oliver Wyman. The former two organizations would provide strategic relationships, and Oliver Wyman would provide consultants to create a subsidiary known as \"Tri International Consulting Group\". The unique arrangement allowed Oliver Wyman to bypass traditional barriers to entry in the Middle East, such as a shortage of [[Arabic]] speakers, and establish long-term work availability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sourceglobalresearch.com/scarce-resources-in-the-gulf-the-problem-is-the-opportunity/|title=Scarce resources in the Gulf: the problem is the opportunity|last=Czerniawska|first=Fiona|date=2014-03-09|website=Source Global Research|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In [[Kuwait]], Oliver Wyman operates exclusively under the Tri International name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy-me.com/news/2368/consultancies-invited-to-bid-for-kuwait-oil-restructuring-project|title=Consultancies invited to bid for Kuwait oil restructuring project|last=|first=|date=2019-10-01|website=Consultancy Middle East|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the group was hired to advise on an [[initial public offering]] of the $90&nbsp;billion Kuwaiti [[stock market]], a process which had been held up for years due to political infighting in the country.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Azhar|first=Saeed|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/kuwait-exchange-advisor-idUSB2N1NW02L|title=Kuwait hires TICG to advise on bourse listing|date=2018-02-12|work=Reuters|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/kuwait/arab-times/20180213/282488594192432|title=Kuwait hires TICG to advise on bourse listing|last=|first=|date=2019-02-13|website=Arab Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm has also advised on debt strategies during periods of oil revenue decline<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/kuwait-hires-oliver-wyman-to-advise-on-debt-amid-bond-plans-1.1831198|title=Kuwait hires Oliver Wyman to advise on debt amid bond plans|last=|first=|date=2016-05-19|website=Gulf News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and planned the installation of smart energy infrastructure across Kuwait.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utilities-me.com/news/11824-kuwait-teams-up-with-telecom-operator-for-smart-utility-meter-project|title=Kuwait teams up with telecom operator for smart utility meter project|last=Asaba|first=Baset|date=2018-09-30|website=Utilities Middle East|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/544176|title=Kuwait residents to save time, money under new platform|last=|first=|date=2018-09-25|website=The Saudi Gazette|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 Bulgarian Bank bid ===\nIn 2016, three firms bid for a project to [[Stress test (financial)|stress test]] Bulgarian banks: management consultancy Oliver Wyman, [[Big Four accounting firms|Big Four]] accounting firm [[Deloitte]], and French firm [[Mazars]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.europawire.eu/bulgarian-national-bank-oliver-wyman-gmbh-mazars-llp-and-deloitte-bulgaria-eood-bid-for-the-assessment-of-the-assets-of-the-banks-in-bulgaria-765432123456790/eu-press-release/2015/09/28/|title=Bulgarian National Bank: Oliver Wyman GmbH, Mazars LLP and Deloitte Bulgaria EOOD bid for the assessment of the assets of the banks in Bulgaria|last=|first=|date=2015-09-28|website=EuropaWire|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman's bid was deemed technically superior to both firms': Mazars' was suspended due to technical errors, and Deloitte scored 44 out of 70 points on the bid assessment compared to Oliver Wyman's 68. However, Oliver Wyman lost the bid to Deloitte due to their high price tag, which valued their work at \u20ac16.72&nbsp;million in comparison to Deloitte's \u20ac800,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accountant.nl/nieuws/2016/1/dure-oliver-wyman-klaagt-vanwege-misgelopen-opdracht/|title=Dure Oliver Wyman klaagt vanwege misgelopen opdracht|last=|first=|date=2016-04-01|website=Accountant.nl|language=nl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm filed an official complaint with the Bulgarian Commission for Protection of Competition for being passed over, citing its long track record, expertise, and quantifiably better offering. However, before the commission began proceedings, Oliver Wyman withdrew their complaint. No reason for the withdrawal was specified.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy.uk/news/3116/oliverwyman-20x-more-expensive-than-deloitte-bulgaria|title=Oliver Wyman 20x more expensive than Deloitte Bulgaria|last=|first=|date=2016-01-04|website=www.consultancy.uk|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017 Australian stress tests ===\nIn 2017, the [[Australian Prudential Regulation Authority]] (APRA) required the [[Commonwealth Bank]] to conduct stress tests due to a series of scandals that had affected the bank's reputation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apra.gov.au/sites/default/files/CBA-Prudential-Inquiry_Final-Report_30042018.pdf|title=Prudential Inquiry into the Commonwealth Bank of Australia (CBA) Final Report|last=|first=|date=2018-04-30|website=Australian Prudential Regulation Authority|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Three panel members were selected to oversee the review. Two voted to appoint Oliver Wyman to conduct the tests, while the other, former chairman of the [[Australian Competition and Consumer Commission]] [[Graeme Samuel]], strongly opposed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/expand-culture-reviews-to-asx200-samuel-20191106-p537v6|title=Expand culture reviews to ASX200: Samuel|last=Seo|first=Bo|date=2019-11-07|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Samuel argued that external consultants should not be hired and that executives who could not resolve their own governance issues should question whether they should remain in positions of leadership. By majority vote, Oliver Wyman was hired for an undisclosed sum in the millions to conduct the tests, and ARPA stated that their final report was \"valuable\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/rear-window/oliver-wyman-a-waste-of-money-graeme-samuel-20191110-p53961|title=Oliver Wyman a waste of money: Graeme Samuel|last=Robin|first=Myriam|date=2019-11-10|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm later conducted similar tests for [[Westpac]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/banking-and-finance/complexity-the-natural-state-of-affairs-at-westpac-report-reveals-20190711-p526ec.html|title=Complexity the 'natural state of affairs at Westpac', report reveals|last=Yeates|first=Clancy|date=2019-07-11|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 Saudi mega-city leak ===\nIn 2017, the [[Kingdom of Saudi Arabia]] announced plans to invest $500&nbsp;billion to develop a futuristic [[smart city]] known as [[Neom]] along the [[Red Sea]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roughmaps.com/destinations/neom-saudi-arabias-500-billion-plan-to-build-a-city-with-gene-editing-and-robotic-dinosaurs/|title=Neom: Saudi Arabia's $500&nbsp;Billion Plan To Build A City With Gene Editing And Robotic Dinosaurs|last=Woods|first=Robbie|date=2020-01-10|website=RoughMaps|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> To help build this city, Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]] hired consultants from Oliver Wyman as well as [[Boston Consulting Group]] and [[McKinsey & Company]] to make recommendations on urban planning, economics and legal systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/neom-what-we-know-saudi-arabia-500bn-mega-city-2019-9|title=Everything we know about Neom, a 'mega-city' project in Saudi Arabia with plans for flying cars and robot dinosaurs|last=Bostock|first=Bill|date=2019-09-23|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Over 2,300 pages of project planning were leaked and published by ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''  in 2019, revealing that the consultancies had made recommendations which relied on technology that did not yet exist such as flying taxis, robot maids, and an artificial moon.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Scheck|first=Justin|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-princes-500-billion-desert-dream-flying-cars-robot-dinosaurs-and-a-giant-artificial-moon-11564097568|title=A Prince's $500&nbsp;Billion Desert Dream: Flying Cars, Robot Dinosaurs and a Giant Artificial Moon|date=2019-07-25|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Jones|first2=Rory|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|last3=Said|first3=Summer}}</ref> In a statement to the press, Neom said \u201cthe involvement of consultants has been productive and valuable\" and that \"Neom is all about things that are necessarily future-oriented and visionary... so we are talking about technology that is cutting edge and beyond, and in some cases still in development and maybe theoretical.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy-me.com/news/2260/consulting-leak-reveals-crazy-details-of-ksas-neom-development|title=Consulting leak reveals crazy details of KSA's Neom development|last=|first=|date=2019-08-01|website=Consultancy Middle East|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe case brought light to potential [[human rights]] abuses involved in the creation of the city, with the firms making recommendations on how to forcibly relocate local tribes, develop a 24/7 surveillance system, and enforce [[Sharia law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/report-saudi-princes-plan-for-flying-taxi-robot-city-w-1836756980|title=Report: Saudi Prince's Plan for Flying Taxi Robot City With 'Giant Artificial Moon' May Be Unrealistic|last=McKay|first=Rom|date=2019-07-27|website=Gizmodo|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It reignited discussion in the [[United States]] regarding Saudi Arabia's dependence on American management firms, which have worked on hundreds of projects for the kingdom.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wald|first=Ellen R.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/18/opinion/saudi-arabia-economy-united-states.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Saudi Arabia Has No Leverage|date=2018-10-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In addition to working on government projects, Oliver Wyman is also a sponsor of the Saudi [[Future Investment Initiative]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy-me.com/news/1182/big-league-consultancies-selected-as-partners-for-ksa-future-investment-event|title=Big-league consultancies selected as partners for KSA future investment event|last=|first=|date=2018-08-06|website=Consultancy Middle East|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Cheetham|first=Joshua|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-45893078|title=Firms defy pressure over Saudi summit|date=2018-10-18|work=BBC News|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\nOliver Wyman is known to encourage consultants to specialize in a practice area relatively early.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caseinterview.com/oliver-wyman-careers|title=Oliver Wyman Careers|last=Cheng|first=Victor|date=2019-07-18|website=Case Interview|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In a quote to ''The New York Times'', a company partner lamented that \u201c[w]hat you find typically with the business schools is that they don\u2019t do customization the way firms like ours do.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tanikawa|first=Miki|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/18/world/asia/designing-business-education-for-a-custom-fit.html|title=Designing Business Education for a Custom Fit|date=2012-05-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast to the traditional \"[[up or out]]\" policy in management consulting, the firm offers a \"direct to partner\" route in six to nine years,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Career Path at Oliver Wyman|url=https://managementconsulted.com/oliver-wyman-interview/|last=|first=|date=2013-08-01|website=Management Consulted|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> where employees who are hired after completing a [[Bachelor's degree]] can be promoted to senior levels without obtaining a [[Master of Business Administration|Masters in Business Administration]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vScNrR_3yNwC&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=oliver+wyman+MBA&source=bl&ots=p5ZrBVTRxx&sig=ACfU3U3PiOIM02VsvCdr-nRU3T6Nl_YFlw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjKubfFporpAhUWvZ4KHQbIBQw4FBDoATACegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=oliver%20wyman%20MBA&f=false|title=25 Top Consulting Firms|publisher=WetFeet, Inc|year=2008|isbn=1582077991|location=|pages=81- 82}}</ref> \n\n== Recruitment ==\n[[File:Ow-1989-mit-recruitment2.png|thumb|A 1989 recruitment flyer published in [[The Tech (newspaper)|''The Tech'']], a campus newspaper at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].|alt=|left|268x268px]]\nOliver Wyman is notoriously challenging to break into, recruiting almost exclusively from elite universities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://poetsandquantsforundergrads.com/2018/05/25/target-schools-for-mbb-consulting-firms/|title=Target Schools For MBB Consulting Firms|last=Carter|first=Andrea|date=2018-05-25|website=Poets & Quants for Undergrads|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestudentroom.co.uk/showthread.php?t=3960753|title=What are the 'Target' Universities for Consultancy firms?|last=|first=|date=|website=The Student Room|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The company has described recruitment as a \"competitive sport... for top students\", utilizing controversial tactics such as declining bonuses to secure employees early.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Story|first=Louise|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/13/business/13bonus.html|title=Clock Ticks, Bonus Ebbs for Recruits|date=2006-10-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Glassdoor]] has ranked the company as the 3rd most difficult to interview for in the world.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Eggers|first=Kelly|url=http://www.fins.com/Finance/Articles/SBB0000872396390443343704577551361228134698/The-25-Toughest-Companies-for-Interviews|title=The 25 Toughest Companies for Interviews|date=2012-07-31|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Applicants go through multiple rounds of phone interviews, leading up to a case interview which tests problem-solving and analytical skills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://targetjobs.co.uk/career-sectors/consulting/451969-oliver-wyman-how-to-get-hired-and-what-its-like-to-work-there|title=Oliver Wyman: how to get hired and what it's like to work there|last=Cleary|first=Matthew|date=2016-11-22|website=TARGET jobs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graduatesfirst.com/oliver-wyman-assessment-tests|title=Oliver Wyman Assessment 2018 {{!}} Aptitude Tests {{!}} CBI {{!}} Case Study Interview|last=|first=|date=|website=Graduates First|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ''Poets & Quants'' has ranked the company as #1 with the Best Interview process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://poetsandquants.com/2019/08/07/consulting-firms-that-pay-the-best-have-the-happiest-employees/|title=Consulting Firms That Pay The Best & Have The Happiest Employees|last=Ethier|first=Marc|date=2019-08-07|website=Poets&Quants|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1990s, Mercer Management Consulting introduced substantial new benefits to employees to better compete with the [[e-commerce]] industry for top graduates. Former Vice Chairman James Down noted that \"[h]istorically, it's been all the major consulting firms and all the major investment banks going after the best and brightest... now that e-commerce firms have joined the fray, we certainly have lost some very good people.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Leonhardt|first=David|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/10/22/business/big-consultants-woo-employees-by-offering-a-piece-of-the-action.html|title=Big Consultants Woo Employees by Offering a Piece of the Action|date=1999-10-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy.uk/news/13958/why-strategy-and-management-consulting-are-so-popular-among-graduates|title=Why strategy and management consulting are so popular among graduates|last=|first=|date=2017-09-11|website=Consultancy UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> But when the [[dot-com bubble]] burst in the early 2000s, this attrition plummeted.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glater|first=Jonathan D.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/14/business/management-business-students-about-face-recruiters-for-banks-consultants-have.html|title=MANAGEMENT: Business Students Do an About-Face; Recruiters for Banks and Consultants Have Regained the Upper Hand|date=2001-02-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n\nMercer did not hire for its prestigious summer internship program in 2002 as a result, stating that they had a \"very large class of new full-time hires.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glater|first=Jonathan D.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/14/business/management-business-students-about-face-recruiters-for-banks-consultants-have.html|title=MANAGEMENT: Business Students Do an About-Face; Recruiters for Banks and Consultants Have Regained the Upper Hand|date=2001-02-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The company defended its controversial decision by claiming that \"[a]ll the firms are looking at similar activities.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://harbus.org/2001/mercer-says-goodbye-to-184/|title=Mercer Says Goodbye To Summer Internships|last=|first=|date=2001-03-05|website=The Harbus|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman did not hire interns again in 2008 due to the [[Great Recession]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=Story|first=Louise|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/02/business/02panic.html|title=Wall Street-Bound Graduates Watch, Wait and Worry|date=2008-04-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and replaced internship offers with full-time positions for graduating candidates in 2020 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/gcreddy42/hiring2020|title=Hiring 2020|last=Gurijala|first=Chaitanya R.|date=|website=GitHub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> New graduates also had their start dates deferred during the [[Economic downturn|economic downturns]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Greenhouse|first=Steven|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/18/business/economy/18grads.html|title=Business Grads Looking Beyond Wall Street|date=2009-04-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2015 to 2018, Oliver Wyman doubled the size of its digital practice. A spokesperson said the firm was \"increasingly hiring people that have those skills\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/6dd91d80-caf8-11e7-8536-d321d0d897a3|title=Management consultants split on how to make digital add up|last=Marriage|first=Madison|date=2018-01-18|website=The Financial Times|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman also pledged to hire qualified [[Refugee|refugees]] during the 2016 [[European migrant crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/cc2c6078-719e-11e5-9b9e-690fdae72044|title=Refugees who seek to build a new life through work|last=Jacobs|first=Emma|date=2015-10-26|website=The Financial Times|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Awards ==\nOliver Wyman is frequently named among the top management firms globally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.preplounge.com/en/consulting-employers/oliver-wyman|title=Career & Application at Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=|website=PrepLounge|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It is colloquially considered a Tier 2 firm, ranking close underneath the [[Big Three (management consultancies)|Big Three]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rocketblocks.me/guide/firm-types.php|title=A field guide to the different types of consulting firms|last=|first=|date=|website=RocketBlocks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman has been ranked in the top 10 of Vault's best consulting firms since the ranking was created in 2001, and currently sits at #5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vault.com/best-companies-to-work-for/consulting/vault-consulting-rankings-top-50|title=Vault Consulting 50|last=|first=|date=|website=Vault|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[:de:brand eins|Brand eins]] magazine has also presented the firm with its Best Consultants Award since the survey was created in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brandeins.de/magazine/brand-eins-thema/consulting-2019/interaktives-ranking-und-bestenliste|title=Die besten Berater Deutschlands|last=|first=|date=|website=Brand eins|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The company is particularly well-known in the financial sector, where it has been awarded the highest possible rating by ''The Financial Times''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ig.ft.com/special-reports/rankings/uk-management-consultants/|title=UK's Leading Management Consultants 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=The Financial Times|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, it was listed as a ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' 100 Best Company to Work For,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/best-companies/oliver-wyman-group/|title=Oliver Wyman Group = 100 Best Companies to Work For|publisher=fortune.com|accessdate=2019-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/press-releases/2019-02-14/oliver-wyman-named-one-of-the-2019-fortune-100-best-companies-to-work-for|title=Oliver Wyman Named One of the 2019 FORTUNE 100 Best Companies to Work For|last=|first=|date=2019-02-14|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ''Fortune'' 100 Best Workplace for Millennials,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greatplacetowork.com/best-workplaces/millennials/2019|title=Best Workplaces for Millennials\u2122 2019|website=Great Place To Work United States|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> [[Stonewall (charity)|Stonewall]] Top 100 LGBT+ Employers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stonewall.org.uk/our-work/campaigns/top-100-employers-2019|title=Top 100 Employers 2019|last=|first=|date=2019-01-07|website=Stonewall|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ''[[Working Mother]]''{{'}}s 100 Best Companies,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.workingmother.com/working-mother-100-best-companies-winners-2019|title=2019 Working Mother 100 Best Companies|website=Working Mother|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> and ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''{{'}}s 50 Companies That Care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/human-interest/people-50-companies-that-care-2019/|title=PEOPLE's 50 Companies That Care: See Our 2019 List of Employers Who Win by Giving Back|last=Herbst|first=Diane|date=2019-07-24|website=People|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman also received a perfect score on the [[Corporate Equality Index]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://assets2.hrc.org/files/assets/resources/CEI-2020.pdf?_ga=2.218153241.1021932257.1581282608-1558750384.1580337746|title=Corporate Equality Index 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=Human Rights Campaign|isbn=978-1-934765-44-9|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It has been ranked on ''The Financial Times'' Best Places to Work in Finance and Consulting (UK) survey<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/24fcfbb6-885d-11e5-90de-f44762bf9896#axzz3rEZgtK4E|title=FT/Glassdoor Best Places to Work in Finance and Consulting UK|publisher=ft.com|accessdate=2017-05-23}}</ref> and ''Fortune''{{'}}s Best Companies to Work For In New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/07/16/best-companies-new-york-2019/|title=The 60 Best Companies to Work for in New York|last=|first=|date=2019-07-16|website=Fortune|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Alumni==\n\n*[[David Akinluyi]], captain of the [[Nigerian national rugby team]]\n*[[Catherine Arnold]], former British diplomat and [[Her Majesty's Ambassador to Mongolia]]\n*[[J. Randolph Babbitt]], former United States [[Federal Aviation Administration]] Administrator<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allgov.com/news/appointments-and-resignations/federal-aviation-administrator-who-is-j-randolph-babbitt?news=838866 |title=Federal Aviation Administrator: Who is J. Randolph Babbitt? |publisher=allgov.com |date=2009-05-20 |accessdate=2017-03-23}}</ref>\n*James R. Barker, former CEO of [[Moore-McCormack|Moore McCormack]] and [[SeaStreak]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.professionalmariner.com/American-Ship-Review-2019/Seastreak-Commodore/|title=Seastreak Commodore: Gotham and beyond in speed and style|last=Gauvin|first=Brian|date=2018-11-05|website=Professional Marin